PiperOrigin-RevId: 378904908
Change-Id: I47f372a344222504d998d00b3f6b6a1c89e88808","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/d20eb1de0902100f218707fd2ea9a5812fc9c005"},{"sha":"d3bbd2ffc930220455e12a9269057f0e200147f9","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix build failure with --config=dbg.

Before, the build would fail with errors such as: "relocation truncated to fit: R_X86_64_32 against .debug_info'". The issue was the debug info was too large. I believe the issue was occurring because offsets into the .debug_info section are stored as 32-bit integers, and so that section cannot exceed 4GiB. To fix, debug info is only included for files under tensorflow/, excluding kernels. This brings the size of the .debug_info section down to about 1.4GiB, well under the 4GiB limit.

Unfortunately, TF kernels and TF dependencies do not have debugging info anymore, but I suspect these are rarely debugged. Debugging info for specific kernels/dependencies can still be explicitly included by the user, e.g. by passing the bazel flags: --config=dbg --per_file_copt=+tensorflow/core/kernels/identity_op.*@-g

See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/48919 for more context.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 378915879
Change-Id: I8379755baf94380ced58bba970ec90a1706ca0c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/c64d579ef7ffbd273240434b9e23e7517cf52d30"},{"sha":"a0360b0b24f5c20d3a654a968ebc5d561c2397c3","author":{"name":"Jiri Simsa","email":"b53bfee97ac78a1d2afd0ef6138945f352c1fa9d@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data] Remove spurious warning.

The mechanism used for checking for the anti-pattern of creating resources within tf.data user-defined functions is incorrect as it does not account for a) the resource creation happening within an `init_scope` (which leads to the warning being emitted spuriously) b) the resource being created in a nested tf.function which has been traced earlier (which leads to not emitting a valid warning).

This CL removes the current mechanism as resources commonly created within user-defined functions -- variables and lookup table -- are hoisted automatically.

[{"sha":"da9c74296d1e41be5a9054b0b507023fec20fb63","author":{"name":"Jeremy Davis","email":"5d9dc440af010fbc6460682e2df8433253afd211@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix some bad indentation.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jeremydavis519/phoenix/commits/da9c74296d1e41be5a9054b0b507023fec20fb63"},{"sha":"18b8b298853eabfa960cbbf756ee6826dc52c3ff","author":{"name":"Jeremy Davis","email":"5d9dc440af010fbc6460682e2df8433253afd211@gmail.com"},"message":"Replace the userspace global bump allocator with an allocator that gets pages from the kernel.

The new allocator still needs work. Specifically, it currently naively assumes that every
allocation or deallocation should correspond with a system call. This wastes a lot of memory
because the kernel can't hand out less than a page at a time, and it also has a really high
latency and low throughput. We can fix both problems by having the allocator ask the kernel
for a large buffer and then use that buffer until it's full.

The buffer should be managed by either a bump allocator or a slab allocator. I'm not sure
right now which would be better.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jeremydavis519/phoenix/commits/18b8b298853eabfa960cbbf756ee6826dc52c3ff"}]

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

This moves the generally applicable short circuit logic from FastAreTensorProtosEqual to AreTensorProtosEqual and only compares proto for large values if false positives are allowed.

I expect the short circuit logic to be beneficial in general given the prevalence for splat tensor attributes. This logic may have some overhead for tiny tensors in computation of number of elements twice. For tensors with large expansion, additional proto comparison should be cheaper compared to proto construction and then serialized string comparison.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Angie3120/moby/commits/1f398f06aa4c533d933bb7335bd9f5047673d7c6"},{"sha":"c7b1e5ba3829a1690a732c19c20d5bf48d58b0d2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"portallocator: log instead of discard port-range failures

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vishalbelsare/moby/commits/1f398f06aa4c533d933bb7335bd9f5047673d7c6"},{"sha":"c7b1e5ba3829a1690a732c19c20d5bf48d58b0d2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"portallocator: log instead of discard port-range failures

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

This moves the generally applicable short circuit logic from FastAreTensorProtosEqual to AreTensorProtosEqual and only compares proto for large values if false positives are allowed.

I expect the short circuit logic to be beneficial in general given the prevalence for splat tensor attributes. This logic may have some overhead for tiny tensors in computation of number of elements twice. For tensors with large expansion, additional proto comparison should be cheaper compared to proto construction and then serialized string comparison.

[{"sha":"dd293327f7a8b164be603461edacdbdf8edc61d4","author":{"name":"Jeremy Davis","email":"5d9dc440af010fbc6460682e2df8433253afd211@gmail.com"},"message":"Add a new shell script for quickly building, but not running or testing, the OS.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jeremydavis519/phoenix/commits/dd293327f7a8b164be603461edacdbdf8edc61d4"},{"sha":"a327ce6780d4348f08282789bdccdc78dca07bfd","author":{"name":"Jeremy Davis","email":"5d9dc440af010fbc6460682e2df8433253afd211@gmail.com"},"message":"Change `SysCallFuture` into a dynamically sized type.

We needed to be able to return more than just a `usize` inside a future sometimes. Now, the
kernel can populate a future as a `SysCallFutureInternal<T>`, where `T: Sized`, and userspace
can read it as a `SysCallFuture`, which is `!Sized`.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jeremydavis519/phoenix/commits/a327ce6780d4348f08282789bdccdc78dca07bfd"},{"sha":"87216118d3ba8dbc2a9259f444f2a6c3e4da2252","author":{"name":"Jeremy Davis","email":"5d9dc440af010fbc6460682e2df8433253afd211@gmail.com"},"message":"Add new system calls for allocating and freeing memory.

There are two options for allocating memory: `memory_alloc` and `memory_alloc_phys`. The latter
guarantees an upper bound on the physical address that's used (since not all devices have 32 or
64 address lines) and also guarantees that the memory will remain resident in memory. (Note that
we don't have any code enforcing that second guarantee yet. We'll have to revisit this when we
implement page-swapping.)

The `memory_free` system call doesn't actually free any memory yet, since we're not yet keeping
track of which blocks each process owns. (We're not even keeping track of processes themselves
yet.) But the API is there, so we can write a global userspace allocator based on `memory_alloc`
and `memory_free`.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jeremydavis519/phoenix/commits/87216118d3ba8dbc2a9259f444f2a6c3e4da2252"}]
